5000|$|The {{conveyance}} or {{delivery of}} possession, known as livery <b>of</b> <b>seisin</b> was effected generally {{on the site}} of the land in a symbolic ceremony of transfer from the feoffor to the feoffee in the presence of witnesses. Written conveyances were customary and mandatory after 1677.|$|R
5000|$|Seisin used in {{the normal}} course of events is of two kinds, [...] "in law" [...] and [...] "in deed". Each carries with it a differing {{strength}} of tenure.It came to be said that later that in the conveyance of a fee by deed of feofment there must be livery <b>of</b> <b>seisin.</b>|$|R
